Hi!! This is Millie… 
I started the “makingmilliestones” page around the time she was born 2.5 years ago.  I had just been through an emotional terrifying pregnancy of numerous appts/scans (in the midst of a pandemic) being told my daughter would most likely be born with Down Syndrome, a multi cystic kidney and and a heart defect.  But for some reason, it was the Down Syndrome diagnosis that scared me the most.  Not knowing much about Down Syndrome and having a false idea of what that meant, I was under the impression having a child with Down Syndrome meant our family’s life would never be the same (emotionally difficult, a financial struggle, a burden on our other child, a marriage strainer and a life devoted to caring for our “disabled” daughter). Well, it was true, our life would never be the same… but NOT in any of the ways I imagined! 

Millie brings us unbelievable happiness, so much love, gratefulness, laughter, pride, and a perspective of life I never knew existed. 

I wanted to share our story so the scared mama (or dad) who just received a diagnosis for their baby, can see all the light that’s ahead.  But I also want them to know they don’t need to feel alone when times feel hard or uncertain.  It’s an emotional wild ride, but one I would buy a ticket for over and over again. 

I want to thank all of our followers who have been right there with us on the ride and who continue to support and cheer for us on all of our adventures ahead. We appreciate you all so so much! 

What questions do you have about us or our story? ⬇️

 #downsyndrome #downsyndromepregnancy #downsyndromediagnosis #trisomy21 #nicubaby #prenataldiagnosis

The walking milestone… it’s required the most amount of patience from me and so much hard work from Millie (and probably a lot of patience from her too). There were many days I doubted when and if she was ever going to walk on her own (these two videos are 6 months apart). But I had to remember that she was perfect, happy, and worthy regardless of when she hit the milestone (or if she hit it at all)! I’ve realized Millie’s determination and her willingness to get back up over and over again was the real reason I was proud of her (not how fast she achieved it).

Did you know straw cups (especially with hard straws) are important for kids with Down Syndrome?  Using a straw cup can help with low tone in the mouth/face and benefit speech because sucking from a straw helps develop those facial movements needed in speech development (like tongue retraction and rounding of the lips). 

Did you also know that I’ve literally tried about 20 different straw cups for Millie?  They were either too hard to clean, the straw wasn’t right, they’d break, or most annoyingly they’d leak or spill everywhere.  Finally, I learned Contigo made a straw cup (called the LEIGHTON) and it checks ALL the boxes!! She can tip it upside down, throw it, set it down wrong, and it doesn’t spill!  Plus, I love that the straw doesn’t move, it’s easy to clean and it’s 100% life proof.  Yay! Thanks @gocontigo .  Now, I need to go buy 5 more:) #contigolifeproof #contigopartner #speechdevelopment #perfectkidscup

Down Syndrome scared me.  I was terrified how our family dynamic would be, how our life would look… But this is how it looks.  There is nothing to fear, and so much to gain.  #trisomy21

Mama.  Something I never thought I could be for her.  Something I was scared to be.  Something I quite frankly didn’t want to be.  All because I feared her diagnosis and what it meant to be her mama.  Would I be strong enough?  Was I equipped for this role?  Could I be what she needed?  Part of me wondered if I would even love her the same way I did her sister (awful I know, but those were the thoughts). 

In those early days, I almost felt ashamed to be her mama.  Had so much guilt…surely I must’ve done something to cause this. 

But now she can scream it from the rooftops.  Because I am SO proud to be her mama!! So overjoyed.  So blessed.  I’d chose to be her mama over and over again ❤️

It’s hard to share those dark beginning feelings because I hate that I felt that way looking back.  It makes my stomach hurt.  But I hope by sharing them, someone with a new diagnosis for their baby can have hope for all the beautiful love and light that is ahead!

#trisomy21 #downsyndrome

Kisses from Millie!  She fought her way through a scary respiratory virus this week and all of your prayers, well wishes and positivity has helped us through it! 💪🏼 thank you!

Since she has Down Syndrome, her low muscle tone and smaller airways can make fighting a virus like this tough on her body.  Her oxygen levels go down and she has a harder time getting the gunk out of her lungs (which is why we use this little lung cupper to help break things up). Last year, she was hit with something similar which required a hospital stay so when she got sick again this week my head started to spin every which way. Every breath she breathed and every cough she coughed had me on edge.  I even packed a hospital bag when I took her to see her doctor.  Being that she is more susceptible and has had some past scary illnesses, my anxiety has been a little high, however I can tell Millie’s body is getting stronger and my head is getting stronger with her! 🙌🏼

#downsyndrome #respiratoryhealth #lunghealth #trisomy21
